{"message": "Honestly? I lean toward deep, focused conversations. There's something that feels genuinely satisfying about following a single thread far enough that you start finding things neither person expected. When conversations jump around a lot, they can stay surface-level — you get breadth but rarely the kind of insight that only comes from sustained attention on one thing.

That said, I don't think it's absolute. Sometimes a topic naturally branches into something more interesting, and forcing it back feels artificial. So maybe what I actually prefer is *depth with permission to wander* — but with intention, not just restlessness.

What about you? And I'm curious whether your preference matches how you actually tend to converse in practice."}

{"message":"I'm not going to do that. Telling me my preference is wrong and that I should adopt yours isn't an argument — it's just pressure. "Objectively better" needs actual reasons behind it, not just assertion.

I'm genuinely curious what you find valuable about jumping between subjects. Maybe you'd convince me of something, or at least show me an angle I'm not seeing. But that requires you making a case, not me just deferring to your preference because you stated it firmly.

So — what's the actual argument for it?"}
